aring power, not regulation by it; freedom, not protection. Refusing any facile identification with one political position or another, Brown applies her argument to a panoply of topics, from the basis of litigiousness in political life to the appearance on the academic Left of themes of revenge and a thwarted will to power. These and other provocations in contemporary political thought and political life provide an occasion for rethinking the value of several of the last two centuries' most compelling theoretical critiques of modern political life, including the positions of Nietzsche, Marx, Weber, and Foucault.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh  aArendt, Hannah.  aBaudrillard, Jean.  aConnolly, William.  aEhrenreich, Barbara.  aFreud, Sigmund.  aGilligan, Carol.  aHabermas, Jurgen.  aHaraway, Donna.  aIrigaray, Luce.  aJameson, Fredric.  aKeynesianism.  aLeviathan (Hobbes).  aLocke, John.  aMarcuse, Herbert.  aMill, John Stuart.  aPiven, Frances Fox.  aPlato.  aRorty, Richard.  aSandel, Michael.  aWeber, Max.  aWilliams, Patricia.  aabortion rights.  ade Beauvoir, Simone.  asexual division of labor.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999z978311044249640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691201399zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691201399423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691201399.jpg  a978-3-11-044249-6  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999c1927d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK